#!/bin/bash
# SessionStart hook: remind the user about their personal skills and prime
# Claude's context so the model knows what's available and when to suggest
# each one.
#
# Output is a JSON blob with two fields:
#   - systemMessage:     shown to the user in the UI at session start
#                        (kept scannable: grouped, one line per skill)
#   - additionalContext: injected into the model's context for this session
#                        (longer: includes "suggest when X" guidance per skill)
#
# To edit the reminder text, modify the jq program below. To disable without
# removing the file, chmod -x this script — the settings.json entry will then
# fail silently (hooks are non-fatal by default).
#
# Currently covers 10 personal skills in ~/.claude/skills/:
#   debug-session, hey-bud, pattern-eval, peon-ping-{config,log,toggle,use},
#   slo-failures-daily, slo-fix-this, teach-me

jq -n '{
  systemMessage: "📋 Personal skills\n\nSLO triage\n• /slo-failures-daily — daily SLO triage + Phase 4 investigation subagents + TDD amenability tags (★★★/★★/✗)\n• /slo-fix-this — single-finding TDD loop (draft test → approval gate → fix → iterate), outputs a local branch\n  Flow: daily → pick ★★★/★★ finding → /slo-fix-this \"<finding>\" → review → commit yourself\n\nDev workflow\n• /hey-bud — build a feature end-to-end (brainstorm → code → review → cleanup → Graphite stack)\n• /debug-session — hypothesis-first debugging with domain knowledge base + post-mortem capture\n• /pattern-eval — analyse recent Claude Code sessions for anti-patterns, output HTML report + config proposals\n\nLearning\n• /teach-me [topic] — Socratic quiz on PostHog architecture, business rules, edge cases, failure modes (bare /teach-me picks a topic)\n\nPeon-ping (exercise + sound)\n• /peon-ping-log [N pushups|squats] — log exercise reps\n• /peon-ping-toggle — mute/unmute sound notifications\n• /peon-ping-use [pack] — set voice pack for this session (GLaDOS, Peon, Kerrigan, …)\n• /peon-ping-config — edit volume, rotation, categories, active pack",
  hookSpecificOutput: {
    hookEventName: "SessionStart",
    additionalContext: "The user has 10 personal skills in ~/.claude/skills/. Suggest them proactively when genuinely relevant, but do NOT over-suggest — these are tools the user already knows about, so only mention when invoking the skill would save them real work.\n\n=== SLO triage (paired workflow, built 2026-04-09) ===\n\n1. /slo-failures-daily — Runs 4 HogQL queries against PostHog project 2 (slo_operation_started / slo_operation_completed events), ranks findings P0/P1/P2 based on failure rate and orphan bursts, dispatches read-only Phase 4 investigation subagents in parallel for actionable findings, and tags each finding by TDD amenability (★★★ ideal unit-test target, ★★ good with caveats, ✗ distributed-systems failure / not TDD-able). Suggest when the user mentions SLO failures, morning triage, production issues, or wants to scan for what broke in the last 24h.\n\n2. /slo-fix-this — Takes a single finding (usually copied from the daily report) and runs a full TDD loop: read-only subagent drafts both a failing test and a fix diff, user approval gate on the test (critical — never skip), then the skill creates a local branch slo-fix/<operation>-<slug>, applies the test, iterates the fix up to 3 times until the test passes, runs a regression check on the containing test file, and hands back. Never commits or pushes — user reviews the branch and handles all git writes manually per their no-auto-commit preference. Suggest after the daily report when the user picks a ★★★ or ★★ finding to action. Will gracefully decline ✗ findings (worker deaths, orphan bursts, distributed-systems failures) rather than forcing a bad test.\n\n=== Dev workflow ===\n\n3. /hey-bud — End-to-end feature build: brainstorming → implementation → code review → cleanup → Graphite branch stacking. Suggest for net-new feature work or any non-trivial change that benefits from the full structured workflow rather than ad-hoc implementation.\n\n4. /debug-session — Hypothesis-first debugging with a domain knowledge base and post-mortem capture. Suggest for any bug investigation, unexpected behavior, flaky test, or production incident. The knowledge base grows across sessions, so using this consistently compounds value.\n\n5. /pattern-eval — Meta-tool: analyses recent Claude Code sessions to identify anti-patterns in prompt quality and validation overhead, produces an HTML report, and proposes config changes. Usually run manually or via weekly cron. Suggest when the user asks about improving collaboration quality, retrospecting on past work, or noticing themselves repeating the same prompt mistakes.\n\n=== Learning ===\n\n6. /teach-me [topic] — Socratic deep-dive into the PostHog codebase. Quizzes the user on architecture, business rules, edge cases, and failure modes for a specific topic. Can be run bare (/teach-me) to pick a topic. Suggest when the user is exploring an unfamiliar area of the codebase and would benefit from active recall rather than passive reading, or when they say they want to learn something properly.\n\n=== Peon-ping (exercise reminders + session sound management) ===\n\n7. /peon-ping-log [N pushups|squats] — Logs exercise reps for the Peon Trainer. Example: /peon-ping-log 25 pushups.\n\n8. /peon-ping-toggle — Toggles peon-ping sound notifications on/off. Use when user wants quiet or wants to re-enable sounds.\n\n9. /peon-ping-use [pack] — Sets which voice pack (GLaDOS, Peon, Kerrigan, etc.) plays for this chat session. Auto-enables session_override rotation mode.\n\n10. /peon-ping-config — Edits peon-ping configuration: volume, pack rotation, categories, active pack, any setting.\n\nRule of thumb: mention these when invoking the skill would save the user real work. Do NOT pepper every response with suggestions — that gets annoying fast."
  }
}'
